Let me re-examine the second Java program's code again. The code is:

public class atcoder_ABC170_A {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new java.io.InputStreamReader(System.in));
        PrintWriter pw = new PrintWriter(System.out);
        String[] input_array = br.readLine().split(" ");
        int result = 0;
        for (String str : input_array) {
            result += 1;
            if ("0".equals(str)) break;
        }
        pw.println(result);
        br.close();
        pw.close();
    }
} Yes, so for each string in the input array (split by spaces), it increments result by 1, then checks if the string is "0". So for input "5", the array has one element, so result becomes 1, then since "5" is not "0", the loop continues, but there are no more elements. So the result is 1. For input "-1", same. So the second program's output is always 1 unless the input contains a "0".
